The scatterplot above illustrates the relationship between miles per gallon and horsepower since mpg is an important indicator of fuel efficiency aiming to improve the car performance and horsepower is the power that engine can produce which is a primary factor in measuring the vehicles performance.The number of cylinders in an engine impact both mpg and horsepower. Based on the plot, the Mpg and horsepower are related and their relationships vary with respect to the cylinder counts. # Creating an outliers function to find outliers in all the columns of the data
identify_outliers <- function(col) {
  # Checking for numeric columns in the data
  if(is.numeric(col)) { 
    # Calculate the mean 
    mean_val <- mean(col)
    # Calculate the standard deviation
    std_dev <- sd(col)
    # Calculate the z scores 
    z_scores <- (col - mean_val) / std_dev
    # Identify the outliers where z scores is greater than the threshold 3
    outliers <- which(abs(z_scores) > 3)
    # Return outliers
    return(outliers)
  } else {
    # else return Null if coloumns are not numeric
    return(NULL)  
  }
}


outliers_list <- lapply(NYC_data, identify_outliers)
# Looping over each column to find the outliers and count the total outliers
# Inititalizing the total outliers count to 0
total_outliers <- 0  
for (x in seq_along(outliers_list)) {
  # Checking for any outliers if they exist
  if(length(outliers_list[[x]]) > 0) {
    num_outliers <- length(outliers_list[[x]])
    # Counting the total outliers 
    total_outliers <- total_outliers + num_outliers  
    # Printing the names of the coloumn that consist of outliers
    cat("Outliers in column", names(outliers_list)[x], ":", num_outliers, "\n")
  }
}
## Outliers in column Admissions : 1917

Question 4

Create a function called annualAdmissions() that derives the total number of reported admissions that transpired each year, for the entire state of NY and displays the results using a line chart. Annotate the chart to show the year with the highest number of admissions. Note: the year should be on the x-axis and the number of admissions on the y-axis. Explain the chart.

# Load the 'dplyr' and 'ggplot2' packages
#library(dplyr)
#library(ggplot2)

# Create a function called annualAdmissions() that derives the total number of reported admissions that transpired in NY and displays the results using a line chart.
# Group by year
# Summarize to get the total number of admissions for the entire state
annualAdmissions <- function (input_data) {
  # Calculate the total number of admissions for each year
  total_num <- input_data %>%
    group_by(year) %>%
    summarise(total_admissions = sum(admissions))
  # Return a line chart
  ggplot(total_num, aes(x=year, y=total_admissions, color=year)) + geom_line() + 
    labs(title="The Total Number of Reported Admissions Per Year in New York State",
         x="Year",
         y="The Number of Admissions",
         caption="Line chart illustrating the trend of total reported admissions to substance abuse treatment program 
         in New York State over time. 
         \nThe data indicates a general decline in admissions from 2010 with a significant decrease after 2015. 
         \nData sourced from 'DATA.NY.GOV'.")
}
annualAdmissions(admissions_data)

Based on the result, we can see that the number of admissions slightly increased from the beginning of the chart until 2010 and then it decreased to around the year 2015. The numbers were remaind relatively consistent with a slight decrease around 2015. After that, there was a significant drop to the year of 2020 and also decreased towards the end of the chart. The reason for the up and downs can be tightly tied with the changes of policy towards the substances use and those downs can be connected to more of the educational effort towards the substances abuse.

Question 6

Filter the data, using a regular expression, and extract all admissions to the various “Rehab” facilities; i.e. your regex should match all facilities that include the word rehab, rehabilitation, etc. Using the filtered data, identify which substance is the most prominent among each age group. Visualize and explain the results.

# Load the 'stringr', 'dplyr', and 'ggplot2' packages
library(stringr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Filter the data, using a regular expression, and extract all admissions to the various “Rehab” facilities
# Detect all the rows with words 'rehab and rehabilitation' in the service type column by ignoring the case
# Print the result
filter_data <- admissions_data %>%
  filter(str_detect(service_type, regex("rehab|rehabilitation", ignore_case=TRUE)))
filter_data

# Use the filtered data, identify which substance is the most prominent among each age group
# Group by age group and substance group
# Summarize the total count for these group
# Pick the maximum count of that substance for each age group
# Print the result
prominent_substance <- filter_data %>%
  group_by(age_group, primary_substance_group) %>%
  summarize(total_counts=n()) %>%
  slice_max(total_counts, n=1)
prominent_substance

# Visualize the result
ggplot(prominent_substance, aes(x=age_group, y=total_counts, fill=primary_substance_group)) + geom_col() +
  labs(title="The Most Prominent Substance Among Each Age group",
       x="Age group",
       y="Total number of admissions",
       caption="Bar chart illustrating the total number of admissions by age group        \nfor the most prominent substances, labeled as 'A' and 'M'.\n\nNote: 'A' represents Alcohol, 'M' represents Marijuana.\n        \nData sourced from 'DATA.NY.GOV'.")

Based on the result, we can see that Marijuana is the most prominent substance among age “18 through 24” group. Alcohol appears to be the most prominent substance among age groups “25 through 34”, “35 through 44”, “45 through 54”, ” 55 and older”. For the age “under 18” group, Marijuana again becomes the most prominent substance. From this observation, we can conclude that Marijuana use is popular among younger people and Alcohol is more popular among older individuals. Marijuana use could be linked with various factors such as societal influences. Alcohol use across 4 age groups and this can be linked with work and life-related stress. People intend to use alcohol to reduce their stress and gradually relied on it.
